<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ What is the different between edge ai chips and data center gpus?  I am going to explain it to you in a way that you never forget it when it comes up in a meeting, interview or talking to a friend. First of all, this is essentially like asking What's the difference between the chips in your phone and the ones in the cloud, and why does it matter?&quot; Edge AI chips are like the tiny brains inside devices like your smartphone or smart speakers. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Thereâ€™s a hidden system that runs the entire internet and almost no one knows about it. Itâ€™s called BGP.  What is BGP? (Border Gateway Protocol) BGP, or Border Gateway Protocol, is like the GPS of the internet. Itâ€™s the system that helps data figure out the best route to travel from one place to another across the massive network of the internet. How It Works: 	â€¢	Internet is a Network of Networks: The internet is made up of thousands of separate networks, each run by different organizations (like Google, your local ISP, or a university). 	â€¢	BGP is the Traffic Manager: BGP is the protocol that these networks use to tell each other which routes they know about. Think of it like a map where each network shares which destinations it can reach. 	â€¢	Routing Decisions: BGP helps each network decide the best path for sending data to any destination. Itâ€™s like choosing the fastest or safest road to get somewhere. #tech #techtok #technology #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/okIsiiKAiAAvPQlAUEAB2BanUBIgPsxMyE8rC?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=JFXyiuCjaFWgkWw%2FBB7%2F1jEhwaM%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/okIsiiKAiAAvPQlAUEAB2BanUBIgPsxMyE8rC?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=JFXyiuCjaFWgkWw%2FBB7%2F1jEhwaM%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/okIsiiKAiAAvPQlAUEAB2BanUBIgPsxMyE8rC?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=JFXyiuCjaFWgkWw%2FBB7%2F1jEhwaM%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Why is every device you own running on the same old chip design? What if I told youâ€¦ your phone, your laptop, your smartwatch even your fridge are all powered by the same kind of chip? Itâ€™s called an ARM chip and itâ€™s everywhere. ARM stands for Advanced RISC Machine, and itâ€™s not a brand itâ€™s a blueprint. ARM Holdings designs the architecture, but companies like Apple, Qualcomm, and Samsung build their own chips based on it. ARM chips are based on RISC Reduced Instruction Set Computing. That means they run simpler instructions, but really fast and really efficiently. Think: fewer steps per task, but optimized for speed and low power. Thatâ€™s why ARM powers most smartphones, tablets, and wearables. Even Appleâ€™s M-series chips in Macs are now ARM-based. This year, over 70% of the worldâ€™s processors use this architecture. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ What is SQL and why is it so important?  Every company has a data problem: too much of it, stored in too many places, and no easy way to get answers. Thatâ€™s where SQL comes in. SQL, Structured Query Language, is how we extract, manipulate, and structure data stored in relational databases. Think millions of rows across multiple tables, users, orders, transactions, all linked by relationships. With just a few lines, SQL can JOIN tables, FILTER records, GROUP data, and even update massive datasets in seconds. Itâ€™s declarative, meaning you tell the database what you want, not how to compute it. And it works across systemsâ€¦PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite, making it the universal language of backend infrastructure. If data is a mess, SQL is the tool that makes it useful. #tech #technology #stem #techeducation #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oAIj2UQNwA7bAeGfEgeqLyASA1IGVABRCWDQbI?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=OIbdJgL2pUQklJnCaXedQnH3%2F5k%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oAIj2UQNwA7bAeGfEgeqLyASA1IGVABRCWDQbI?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=OIbdJgL2pUQklJnCaXedQnH3%2F5k%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oAIj2UQNwA7bAeGfEgeqLyASA1IGVABRCWDQbI?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=OIbdJgL2pUQklJnCaXedQnH3%2F5k%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ What is kubernetes? Here is a simple explanation so you can easily understand it whether in a meeting, interview etc.  Kubernetes is important because it makes running large, complex applications much easier and more reliable. Instead of manually managing every part of your app like starting and stopping services, handling traffic spikes, or fixing crashes. Kubernetes automates all of that. It works by running containers (small, packaged parts of an app) across a group of machines, organizing them into pods, and making sure everything stays healthy and balanced. If something breaks, Kubernetes fixes it. If your app needs to scale to handle more users, it does that too. Itâ€™s especially useful for modern apps built with microservices, where managing everything by hand would be overwhelming. #tech #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ocgBELEQCgAIMAjJAI1LeAhACntGBLvFcSf4eI?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2F%2FZx6sfhwDtwmWRNAPqWcLm7A00%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ocgBELEQCgAIMAjJAI1LeAhACntGBLvFcSf4eI?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2F%2FZx6sfhwDtwmWRNAPqWcLm7A00%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ocgBELEQCgAIMAjJAI1LeAhACntGBLvFcSf4eI?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2F%2FZx6sfhwDtwmWRNAPqWcLm7A00%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ When you send a message or load a website, your data travels across a global infrastructure, one that most people never see. Over 99% of international internet traffic is carried by submarine fiber-optic cables laid across the ocean floor. These cables transmit data as pulses of light, using total internal reflection to bounce signals down glass strands at nearly the speed of light. Once your data reaches land, it's routed through a complex mesh of interconnected networks using protocols like BGP (Border Gateway Protocol), which determines the most efficient path to the destination. Routers act like traffic controllers, making real-time decisions to avoid congestion and outages. And in places where cables canâ€™t reach, think rural areas, ships at sea, or remote islands, satellites and wireless networks take over, using radio frequencies to transmit data with higher latency but broad coverage. All of this happens in milliseconds, creating the illusion of instant connectivity! #tech #technology #stem #coding #ai #developer #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/og3lImFzAKS8MGZeCADAQtfhjyPg2EHIAtE0fY?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=uTkr%2FfhlNVCt%2FDZ%2Bsa0U4HG9sno%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/og3lImFzAKS8MGZeCADAQtfhjyPg2EHIAtE0fY?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=uTkr%2FfhlNVCt%2FDZ%2Bsa0U4HG9sno%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/og3lImFzAKS8MGZeCADAQtfhjyPg2EHIAtE0fY?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=uTkr%2FfhlNVCt%2FDZ%2Bsa0U4HG9sno%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

At its core, it utilizes three main APIs:  PRAW for Reddit data collection, TextBlob for ML-based sentiment analysis, and yfinance for real-time stock data. The architecture implements a multi-layer approach. The data collection layer fetches posts from financial subreddits, while the ML layer processes text through TextBlob's pre-trained NLP model. This model analyzes linguistic patterns, contextual relationships, and negations to generate sentiment polarity scores ranging from -1 to 1. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ What happens when a robot doesnâ€™t know what to do? No script. No instructions. Just a task â€” and it has to figure it out. Reinforcement learning lets a robot explore. Try something. Get a reward if it works, a penalty if it doesnâ€™t. Over time, it builds a policy â€” its internal guide for what to do next. But not all robots learn this way. Some copy humans â€” thatâ€™s imitation learning. Others follow strict rules. The best systems blend all three. A delivery robot, for example, might use physics to stay upright, imitation to handle crowds, and reinforcement learning to react to surprises. To make that safe, we start with sim-to-real transfer â€” the robot trains in simulation first. Then we use human-in-the-loop learning â€” people guide and reinforce good behavior. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ What is transfer learning in AI? Here is a simple explanation so you never forget it in a meeting or talking to someone. Researchers at Cornell discovered something fascinating about artificial neural networks: they found that the first layers of these networks learn universal features that work across almost any visual task. This is what we call transfer learning. Instead of starting from scratch every time, AI can take knowledge from one task and apply it to another. Here's what this means in practice: In a groundbreaking study at Google, researchers took an AI model trained on 1.2 million random images and repurposed it to identify medical conditions in x-rays. The transfer learning approach achieved 89% accuracy with just 10% of the usual training data needed. This isn't just theoretical - transfer learning is revolutionizing everything from drug discovery to climate science. Stanford researchers found it can reduce AI training time by up to 75% while using significantly less energy. So next time someone tells you AI learns from scratch each time - well, now you know better. #tech #technology #ai #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/owIBiigBAd8PCy1pvzQAA6EvhAECIAFcBeoOio~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/o8KvIQfgMGauoRR7AQ8dA9AAVWq6AeKiff0M1f.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=e3ZRFLzsznG1LASj6R%2FxMaDmKhE%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/owIBiigBAd8PCy1pvzQAA6EvhAECIAFcBeoOio~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/o8KvIQfgMGauoRR7AQ8dA9AAVWq6AeKiff0M1f.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=e3ZRFLzsznG1LASj6R%2FxMaDmKhE%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/owIBiigBAd8PCy1pvzQAA6EvhAECIAFcBeoOio~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/o8KvIQfgMGauoRR7AQ8dA9AAVWq6AeKiff0M1f.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=e3ZRFLzsznG1LASj6R%2FxMaDmKhE%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Why do versions of Y2K keep happening ðŸ¤”ðŸ¤¯ In 2014, the internet faced a critical breaking point that most people have never heard of - The 512K Day Crisis. But what exactly made this day so important? See, the internet works through routers that keep a special memory table of all possible paths to send data - like a massive address book. But in the 1990s, router manufacturers set a hard memory limit of 512K entries, thinking we'd never need more than that. This caused a massive problem when the internet grew beyond what anyone expected. Enter August 12, 2014 - now known as 512K Day. When the routing table exceeded 512K entries, routers worldwide began failing. Major websites went dark, internet service providers experienced outages, and thousands of networks started having mysterious problems. The internet was essentially running out of memory.  #tech #technology #coding #stem #developer #futuretech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o42g6vIphblAiqCAtEQAZBHEiMAIUdZBiSzUp?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=BpXIabJkljTjRmdcc54JvRz%2BrWs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o42g6vIphblAiqCAtEQAZBHEiMAIUdZBiSzUp?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=BpXIabJkljTjRmdcc54JvRz%2BrWs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o42g6vIphblAiqCAtEQAZBHEiMAIUdZBiSzUp?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=BpXIabJkljTjRmdcc54JvRz%2BrWs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Right now, there's a global race to build a quantum internet under our oceans, and it could make hacking nearly impossible. Let me explain why this is wild. Today's undersea cables use light to send data with digital keys for encryption.  But here's the problem - hackers can secretly copy this data without leaving a trace. Enter quantum communication. It uses the rules of quantum physics to protect data. And here's the wild part - scientists just proved it works. In a recent breakthrough, researchers in Germany successfully transmitted quantum data while actively trying to hack it. Here's how: Instead of sending normal binary code, the system uses individual light particles - photons - to create an unhackable key. Try to spy on these photons, and they literally collapse. Even wilder? Scientists at Northwestern University just showed they can send quantum data through the same cables that carry our regular internet. Meaning we might not need to rebuild the entire internet to make it quantum-secure. With 99% of international data flowing through undersea cables, making them quantum-secure isn't just cool science - it's becoming a national security priority. So what do you think happens when hacking becomes nearly impossible? <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ This might be the most inefficient technology we still use today and it's in the name of every single file on your computer. Those three little letters at the end of your files? They're from a time when computers were so limited, they couldn't even handle long file names.  We're talking back in the 1980s when filenames could only be eight characters long, followed by a dot and three more characters. But here's the thing that's going to blow your mind - modern computers don't even need these extensions! They're smart enough to look inside files and know exactly what they are, using something called &quot;magic numbers. &quot; It works like this: Every file has a special code at the beginning that tells the computer what kind of file it is. It's like DNA for your documents. Your computer could just read this instead of relying on those three letters at the end. So why are we still using this ancient system? Because changing it would be like trying to convince everyone in the world to switch which side of the road they drive on... at the same time. Sometimes the most powerful force in technology isn't innovation - it's habit. #tech #techtok #technology #stem #FutureOfTech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYwK9AkvQSAgKIQPEPLeCEg8TCfAicIfjAGzIp~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/okIjwSQe1E9IAQGbEgemLfASAiI3FASpCQPPhI.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=YHNnme4DCkP48KLHzuBCFe%2Bz25g%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYwK9AkvQSAgKIQPEPLeCEg8TCfAicIfjAGzIp~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/okIjwSQe1E9IAQGbEgemLfASAiI3FASpCQPPhI.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=YHNnme4DCkP48KLHzuBCFe%2Bz25g%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYwK9AkvQSAgKIQPEPLeCEg8TCfAicIfjAGzIp~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/okIjwSQe1E9IAQGbEgemLfASAiI3FASpCQPPhI.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=YHNnme4DCkP48KLHzuBCFe%2Bz25g%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Ever wonder who's in charge of the internet? Like, ACTUALLY in charge? While no one technically &quot;controls&quot; the internet, there are 13 root servers that act as its ultimate source of truth. Think of them like the internet's supreme court. When your device needs to find something online, these 13 servers are the final authority on where to go. And here's the wild part - the number 13 isn't random! It comes from a technical limit from the 1980s. Each lookup request can only be 512 bytes - about the size of a tweet. With each server needing 40 bytes... you get exactly 13 servers! But there aren't actually just 13 physical servers. There are hundreds of copies spread around the world, each working as part of a massive backup system! If all these root servers somehow went down at once with no backups, the entire internet would start breaking within hours. Your apps wouldn't work. Websites would become unreachable. Email? Forget about it. But the system is designed so that can't easily happen. When hackers tried to attack all 13 root servers in 2002, the backup copies kept everything running smoothly. Pretty smart, right? But wait - why can't we just make the packet bigger and have more root servers? <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Why did most major tech companies decide to make their AI assistants female?  Siri, Alexa, Google assistant - they all started with women's voices. And no, it wasn't a coincidence. If you're thinking of Siri or Alexa, you're probably hearing a female voice. But why is that? It's not just a coincidence. Back in the 1960s, a man named John Pierce was working at Bell Labs, trying to create the first computer-generated voice. And he made a key observation: people were already super comfortable getting help from women's voices. Why? Because for decades, telephone operators were exclusively female. But here's where it gets really interesting. Studies showed that people didn't just accept female voices â€“ they actively preferred them in helper roles. We found them more welcoming, more trustworthy, and yes, less threatening than male voices. So when tech companies started creating AI assistants, they weren't just copying what came before â€“ they were tapping into decades of social conditioning. Pretty wild, right?" fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8PTbpZDRKQzEUiAFPC6VZ6BhiAA5BSiIELAm~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oUBiwCQEvSpPSJAEzAiibATZ5KI9PU5A5BUm6.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=N08pOWOj8H%2BgxmcJ%2Bxy2aHBPe3U%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8PTbpZDRKQzEUiAFPC6VZ6BhiAA5BSiIELAm~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oUBiwCQEvSpPSJAEzAiibATZ5KI9PU5A5BUm6.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=N08pOWOj8H%2BgxmcJ%2Bxy2aHBPe3U%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8PTbpZDRKQzEUiAFPC6VZ6BhiAA5BSiIELAm~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oUBiwCQEvSpPSJAEzAiibATZ5KI9PU5A5BUm6.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=N08pOWOj8H%2BgxmcJ%2Bxy2aHBPe3U%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Have you ever felt like something's... off about the internet lately?  Like you're seeing the same content over and over, or conversations that feel weirdly artificial? You're not alone - and there's actually a fascinating theory about this. It's called the Dead Internet Theory.  See here's the thing: Studies show that over 40% of all internet traffic isn't human at all - it's automated bots. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ There's something weird happening to the internet right now, and almost no one is talking about it. We're running out of addresses - not physical addresses, but IP addresses.  You know, those number sequences that help computers find each other online? Here's the thing: When the internet was built, they created a system called IPv4 that allows for about 4 billion unique addresses. In 1981, that seemed like way more than we'd ever need. But now? Yeah, we've basically used them all up. Think of it like a phone number system. Imagine if we could only use 7 digits. Eventually, we'd run out of new numbers to give people. That's exactly what's happening with IP addresses. And when we run out completely?  New devices won't be able to connect to the internet properly, and services like video calls and online gaming will start breaking down because devices can't establish direct connections anymore. The solution exists - it's called IPv6, and it can handle a mind-blowing 340 undecillion addresses. #tech #stem #futuretech #coding " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o0IDnkAhyhmUECJfdYRB0oAAECJGRtAEsQfFRR~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oMAQAf1lBgCziAJCyRiRKmEGyBEIkDwoyUISIA.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=H8%2BJL1z%2FewG654KB7pNGfvvFTI8%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o0IDnkAhyhmUECJfdYRB0oAAECJGRtAEsQfFRR~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oMAQAf1lBgCziAJCyRiRKmEGyBEIkDwoyUISIA.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=H8%2BJL1z%2FewG654KB7pNGfvvFTI8%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o0IDnkAhyhmUECJfdYRB0oAAECJGRtAEsQfFRR~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oMAQAf1lBgCziAJCyRiRKmEGyBEIkDwoyUISIA.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=H8%2BJL1z%2FewG654KB7pNGfvvFTI8%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ What is zero-proof-knowledge and why is it such a big deal?  Instead of sending your actual password, your device turns it into a massive number that can't be reversed. When you log in, the website sends a random challenge, and your device responds with mathematical proof - like solving a puzzle that only someone with your password could solve. Companies like BMW are already using this for massive transactions. They can prove they made valid payments for thousands of parts without revealing any details. Their competitors see nothing, but everyone knows the transaction is legit. The best part? Your password never leaves your device. If a company gets hacked, your password can't be stolen because they never had it. And with billions of passwords leaked last year, that's a game-changer. #tech #stem #futuretech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/ogYGLEfcdI7AcEbNIAAtIesXS1DYPQAghCLjge~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oIAAdQAXNQPA8fZ1ykQlEWDIjCtMOgbSoI8Eee.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=2ZJR%2FI%2Fpm8nEa3f44n%2Fqe4awcO4%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/ogYGLEfcdI7AcEbNIAAtIesXS1DYPQAghCLjge~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oIAAdQAXNQPA8fZ1ykQlEWDIjCtMOgbSoI8Eee.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=2ZJR%2FI%2Fpm8nEa3f44n%2Fqe4awcO4%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/ogYGLEfcdI7AcEbNIAAtIesXS1DYPQAghCLjge~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oIAAdQAXNQPA8fZ1ykQlEWDIjCtMOgbSoI8Eee.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=2ZJR%2FI%2Fpm8nEa3f44n%2Fqe4awcO4%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Palali Music çš„ sonido original åˆ›ä½œçš„ Even using incognito mode wonâ€™t protect you from this. But there is a browser that allows your to turn it off (for the most part)  Every website you visit is collecting over 50 pieces of invisible information about you right now. Not just your location or device - but things like how your keyboard types, how your mouse moves, even how your battery drains. Together, they create something called a digital fingerprint, and it can identify you with 99% accuracy.  And here's where it gets interesting - companies aren't just collecting this data, they're selling it. Advertisers, data brokers, and analytics companies all want your digital fingerprint because it helps them build detailed profiles of your habits. They use this to predict what you'll buy, when you'll buy it, and how much you'll spend. The wild part? Unlike cookies, you can't delete this. Clear your history, use incognito mode, even switch browsers - your fingerprint follows you. Every website you visit becomes another piece of your digital shadow, painting an increasingly detailed picture of your online life. #tech #technology #stem #futuretech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ocm9kPAEeAEeAiGvISzIEvQguLj9JC6AeSIICo?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=oSBIaEa7%2F7NmSErxjRBrqNX3k4c%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ocm9kPAEeAEeAiGvISzIEvQguLj9JC6AeSIICo?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=oSBIaEa7%2F7NmSErxjRBrqNX3k4c%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ocm9kPAEeAEeAiGvISzIEvQguLj9JC6AeSIICo?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=oSBIaEa7%2F7NmSErxjRBrqNX3k4c%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Have you ever wondered how your phone knows which signals are meant for YOU among the millions flying through the air right now? Every second, there are countless phone calls zooming through the space around us. But your phone finds exactly what it needs through a process called frequency-division multiplexing. Here's how it works: Your phone and cell towers communicate using unique frequency bands and digital codes. - kind of like having a private language that only they understand. When I make a call, my phone scrambles the signal using this special code. Other phones detect these radio waves, but can't decipher them. But here's the weird part - sometimes your phone shows full bars, but nothing works! This is because they only measure downlink RSSI. You could have perfect reception, but if thousands of phones are overwhelming the tower's processing capacity or your uplink is weak, you'll still have connection issues. #tech #technology #coding #stem " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oI1DSHQQE3DAgJeFacCbEnSQkA9BREAAICG9fE~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oEEBIACAjpLAAcGPYLCQecqu0hfIvIAgSe0DEa.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2BXFcaYuIKVNb4zF9Fx81PKeaNNI%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oI1DSHQQE3DAgJeFacCbEnSQkA9BREAAICG9fE~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oEEBIACAjpLAAcGPYLCQecqu0hfIvIAgSe0DEa.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2BXFcaYuIKVNb4zF9Fx81PKeaNNI%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oI1DSHQQE3DAgJeFacCbEnSQkA9BREAAICG9fE~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oEEBIACAjpLAAcGPYLCQecqu0hfIvIAgSe0DEa.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2BXFcaYuIKVNb4zF9Fx81PKeaNNI%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Palali Music çš„ sonido original åˆ›ä½œçš„ You might think the internet was built by some giant tech company, or maybe a government agency. But the system that powers literally everything you do online? It was created by two guys who were trying to solve an impossible problem. #tech #technology #coding #stem #futuretech  In 1974, different computer networks were like countries with completely different postal systems. If you were on one network, you couldn't send anything to another. They spoke different languages, used different rules - everything. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Anderson .Paak çš„ Make It Better (Instrumental) åˆ›ä½œçš„ Here's something wild - the cloud wasn't invented by tech giants. It actually started way back in the 1960s with something called time-sharing. See, computers used to be MASSIVE and cost millions. So companies would rent out computing time, kind of like splitting a vacation home with strangers. You'd get your slice of computing power when you needed it. Fast forward to 2006. Amazon had this fascinating problem - they'd built this HUGE computing infrastructure for their holiday shopping season, but it sat mostly empty the rest of the year. Then someone had a brilliant idea: &quot;What if we rented out our extra capacity?&quot; That's how Amazon Web Services was born. But here's where it gets really interesting. Traditional servers are like having a whole house to yourself - you pay for everything, even the rooms you don't use. Modern cloud computing? It's more like a magical house that grows and shrinks exactly as you need it. We've gone from sharing time on massive computers, to renting virtual servers, to not thinking about servers at all (using containers). And that's transforming how we build everything from your favorite apps to entire companies." fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYIA2OWInE2AfgjPiSQADFECAwDPreAaEfm7HS?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2BnoVgwErAzJb5PnAZWqAqCzWUYs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYIA2OWInE2AfgjPiSQADFECAwDPreAaEfm7HS?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2BnoVgwErAzJb5PnAZWqAqCzWUYs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYIA2OWInE2AfgjPiSQADFECAwDPreAaEfm7HS?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2BnoVgwErAzJb5PnAZWqAqCzWUYs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Would you live in this underwater habitat?  In 2025, humans might finally have a new home - underwater. Right now, scientists can only spend 10 minutes working at deep depths before needing 6 hours to decompress. This could turn those minutes into months of research time. This is Vanguard, and it's about to change how we explore our oceans. Here's what makes it work: Imagine a shipping container-sized home that keeps you alive 100 meters underwater. The secret? It's built by robots. These aren't just any robots. They're using wire-arc additive manufacturing - basically 3D printing meets welding. Six robotic arms work together to build massive pressure-resistant hulls up to 6 meters wide. But here's the wild part - inside Vanguard, you're breathing 98% helium. Why? Because at that depth, nitrogen becomes toxic. But helium creates a whole new problem.  It's so thermally conductive that they have to heat it to 31Â°C just to keep the habitat comfortable! The tech keeping you alive runs on floating solar farms and specially designed underwater batteries - because normal ones? Helium would destroy them. This isn't just cool tech - it's opening up the 90% of ocean biodiversity we've never been able to properly study. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Anderson .Paak çš„ Make It Better (Instrumental) åˆ›ä½œçš„ What if I told you that most of the encryption protecting our internet is about to become... breakable? Right now, our online security uses mathematical puzzles that are basically impossible for regular computers to solve. Like, it would take them thousands of years. But quantum computers? They could crack these puzzles in weeks. Maybe even days. That's why this is fascinating - a team of cryptographers, led by Joppe Bos, created something called CRYSTALS-Kyber. Instead of using traditional math problems, it uses something called lattice-based cryptography. Imagine a grid in multiple dimensions, with thousands of points. Your secret message is hidden using math that involves finding specific paths between these points. Even quantum computers get lost trying to solve it! The coolest part? This isn't just theoretical. Google's Chrome browser is already using it. Your future credit cards will use it. Even your car might use it. This is how we quantum-proof the internet - not with bigger locks, but with better math. #tech #technology #quantumcomputing #coding #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oIQ1fUQdfAEVYMBNBBRn7HBk1iBJiEbsXdWIWz?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=U4Ud2o%2BCunEiLhmygMfjsWtnHnc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oIQ1fUQdfAEVYMBNBBRn7HBk1iBJiEbsXdWIWz?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=U4Ud2o%2BCunEiLhmygMfjsWtnHnc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oIQ1fUQdfAEVYMBNBBRn7HBk1iBJiEbsXdWIWz?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=U4Ud2o%2BCunEiLhmygMfjsWtnHnc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ In 1985, there was a massive problem threatening to break the entire internet. But most people don't know about the woman who solved it - Radia Perlman. See, early computer networks had a critical flaw. T o make sure messages got through, networks would create multiple paths between computers. But this caused an explosive problem called a broadcast storm - messages would loop endlessly until the entire network collapsed. Enter Radia Perlman. In just one weekend, she wrote the Spanning Tree Protocol - an algorithm that automatically prevents these loops. And here's the wild part - it's still running in almost every network today. Perlman says her more important work was making networks &quot;self-healing&quot;  What Perlman considers her more significant contribution was developing &quot;Network Fault T olerance&quot; protocols. These algorithms automatically detect network failures and reroute traffic in milliseconds - without any human intervention.  Her work on the IS-IS (Intermediate System to Intermediate System) protocol became fundamental to how large networks maintain reliability. #tech #technology #coding #stem #futuretech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8frzupEtBgio55EAIpA3AAP8ldotzGuBCItiB?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=G4OVWlzkVmMWp8VXpryh5dwX1jc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8frzupEtBgio55EAIpA3AAP8ldotzGuBCItiB?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=G4OVWlzkVmMWp8VXpryh5dwX1jc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8frzupEtBgio55EAIpA3AAP8ldotzGuBCItiB?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=G4OVWlzkVmMWp8VXpryh5dwX1jc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ This might be one of the most brilliant security features ever invented. And you're using it every single day without even knowing it. When you type your password into a website, you probably think it's stored somewhere, right? Wrong. What's actually stored is complete gibberish - and that's exactly how it should be. Let's say your password is &quot;DogLover123&quot; . When you create an account, the website runs it through something called SHA-256 - a cryptographic hash function that's basically a superhero of the internet. It puts your password through 64 rounds of mathematical operations. So &quot;DogLover123&quot; becomes this: &quot;8d969eef6ecad3c29a3a629280e686cf0c3f5d5a86aff3ca12020c923adc6c92&quot; This 256-bit output looks random, but it's actually the result of precise mathematical chaos. But wait - if websites don't know your actual password, how do they check if you typed it correctly? Here's where it gets interesting: SHA-256 will always create the exact same output for the same input. So when you log in, they run your password through those same 64 rounds of mathematical operations and check if the gibberish matches. And here's what makes SHA-256 incredible - it's mathematically impossible to find two passwords that create the same output. Even changing one letter creates a completely different hash. #tech #technology #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oM2qAoiABKIiZiJEsGUApLEQrIBBiNuQ2DAhP?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=8Mw5t1gi4DRoNT2wvP8QlnyXOqk%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oM2qAoiABKIiZiJEsGUApLEQrIBBiNuQ2DAhP?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=8Mw5t1gi4DRoNT2wvP8QlnyXOqk%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oM2qAoiABKIiZiJEsGUApLEQrIBBiNuQ2DAhP?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=8Mw5t1gi4DRoNT2wvP8QlnyXOqk%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Ever wondered who invented the text message? Well - like most world-changing inventions, it was a bit complicated.. Let me explain.   In 1984, two engineers were working when they had an idea: what if phones could send short written messages?  But here's what's fascinating - they noticed something when studying postcards. Most messages people wrote naturally fell under 160 characters. That's why early texts had that limit! <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Palali Music çš„ sonido original åˆ›ä½œçš„ 99% of the internet runs through cables under water. But why wouldn't we just use satellites? It comes down to three main things: First - it comes down to latency. That's the time it takes for your data to make the trip. Through satellites? Your signal has to travel all the way to space and back While cables take a shortcut across the ocean. That's why when I send this message to someone in Europe, it only takes about 100 milliseconds through a cable. Through a satellite? More like 700 milliseconds. Second - these cables are data powerhouses. A single modern cable can carry up to 200 terabits per second. That's like downloading 25,000 HD movies... every second. And third - they're actually more reliable than satellites. They're protected from weather, solar storms, and space debris. Though occasionally they do get attacked by sharks. Yes, really. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Did you know your private browser mode isn't really keeping you private at all? Let's break down what actually happens when you open a private browsing window. Your browser creates a temporary session - no previous cookies, no browsing history, no saved passwords. When you close the window, all of that session data disappears from your device. That's it. But here's the crucial part: Your internet service provider still sees all your traffic. Your school or workplace network still logs every site you visit. And the websites themselves? They know exactly when you arrive and what you do there. It's similar to using a store but asking them not to save your receipt. The security cameras are still recording, the payment processor still sees your transaction, and the store still knows a customer came in - they just won't have it in their local records. What makes this even more significant is how companies can still track you in private mode using your IP address and something called browser fingerprinting - the unique way your browser and device identify themselves to websites. Even without cookies, these technical signatures can reveal who you are. Send this to someone who might need this reminder! #tech #technology #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/og6AwySfAQVRpJkdGeeIFgLBrIQcIALJADAkeG?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=NyI%2BeZN1%2F4o%2BZhMkiCrlLnp8evo%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/og6AwySfAQVRpJkdGeeIFgLBrIQcIALJADAkeG?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=NyI%2BeZN1%2F4o%2BZhMkiCrlLnp8evo%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/og6AwySfAQVRpJkdGeeIFgLBrIQcIALJADAkeG?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=NyI%2BeZN1%2F4o%2BZhMkiCrlLnp8evo%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Why are some time zones 30 minutes off? And what does that have to do with computers freaking out about leap seconds? Here's the thing - the whole world used to run on local time. Noon was when the sun was highest in your specific location. But then trains happened. Railway companies needed standardized time to make schedules work. So in 1884, we divided the world into 24 time zones. Clean and simple, right? Not exactly. Because some countries said &quot;we're gonna do our own thing.&quot; India split the difference between two zones with a +5:30 offset. Nepal went even further with +5:45. And computers? They HATE this. See, computers need precise time for everything from security certificates to financial transactions. They use UTC - Universal Coordinated Time. But Earth's rotation isn't perfectly consistent. So scientists occasionally add &quot;leap seconds&quot; to keep atomic clocks synchronized with Earth's rotation. The last time this happened, some major websites crashed. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Palali Music çš„ sonido original åˆ›ä½œçš„ Learning about this blew my mind. There is a lot more information on ICANN on their blog! Also, although we are referencing â€œ7 peopleâ€ in the video, that is a reference often used but it is much more complicated.. here is a snippet from their website..  There are around fifty different experts who are directly involved in key ceremonies. Twenty-one of these are selected from the global Internet community. They are divided into three groups of seven people. Each group has a different purpose. Because we need people from these groups to participate in key ceremonies as part of the security protection for the key signing key, it is often simplified to the idea that there are seven keys to the Internet, or there are seven people that control the Internet. This, however, masks the true complexity that involves many levels of overlapping controls. The complete design requires far more than seven individuals or seven keys to access or use the root zone key signing key. #tech #technology #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o06DnQ6IAyGfAQOIWILdAfDGAAkBAFh1efhRlJ?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=CAvX04Z5fE3cnWue8FQET1%2BXPxs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o06DnQ6IAyGfAQOIWILdAfDGAAkBAFh1efhRlJ?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=CAvX04Z5fE3cnWue8FQET1%2BXPxs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o06DnQ6IAyGfAQOIWILdAfDGAAkBAFh1efhRlJ?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=CAvX04Z5fE3cnWue8FQET1%2BXPxs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Melodality çš„ Artificial Intelligence åˆ›ä½œçš„ The most inefficient design in modern technology is sitting right in front of you. It's your keyboard and there is a really interesting reason why we can't get rid of it. In the 1870s, early typewriters had a serious problem. When people typed too quickly, the mechanical arms would crash into each other and jam. The solution? Keyboard designer Christopher Sholes rearranged the letters to put commonly used pairs far apart. Some people say the QWERTY layout already existed and was invented by telegram operators. But you can decide that. Regardless, this design helped slow typing down.  Think about it: 'E' and 'R' are typed with different fingers. 'T' and 'H' are on opposite sides. This isn't random - it's intentionally inefficient to prevent those mechanical jams. When computers came along, we no longer needed this slow-down design. We could arrange letters any way we wanted. In fact, in 1936, August Dvorak created a scientifically optimized keyboard layout that was 74% more efficient. But by then, millions of people had already learned QWERTY. The inefficient design had won. #tech #technology #coding #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ognXBfx4IAOSC2yEEmAc4BAEARFOaJfxMQLDDE?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=8hPbVxU%2BDrJR%2B0uBxGSDjLrMKtY%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ognXBfx4IAOSC2yEEmAc4BAEARFOaJfxMQLDDE?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=8hPbVxU%2BDrJR%2B0uBxGSDjLrMKtY%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ognXBfx4IAOSC2yEEmAc4BAEARFOaJfxMQLDDE?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=8hPbVxU%2BDrJR%2B0uBxGSDjLrMKtY%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Melodality çš„ Artificial Intelligence åˆ›ä½œçš„ Google's quantum computer did something that would take our fastest supercomputers 10 SEPTILLION years... in just five minutes! Let me break down how that's even possible. Our normal computers, work with bits - basically tiny switches that are either ON or OFF. That's it. Just 1s and 0s. Let's say you wanted to crack a password with 10 characters. A regular computer would have to try each combination one at a time - that could take years! But a quantum computer? It could try all possible combinations simultaneously. It's like having millions of computers working in parallel! This is possible because quantum computers use qubits, which can be ON and OFF at the same time. I know, I know. How is that possible? Well, this is where things get REALLY interesting. Researchers use individual atoms, super-cooled to near absolute zero - that's colder than space itself! At these temperatures, atoms start behaving according to quantum mechanics, where the normal rules of physics just... don't apply. But here's the catch - it's INCREDIBLY difficult to maintain this quantum state. Think about trying to balance a pencil on its tip... while riding a bicycle... during an earthquake. That's STILL easier than keeping qubits stable! Scientists call this problem &quot;decoherence. &quot; Right now, the best quantum computers have about 100 working qubits. But here's something wild - a quantum computer with just 300 qubits would be able to perform more simultaneous calculations than there are atoms in the observable universe! And the coolest part? We're just scratching the surface. #tech #technology #stem #techexplained #quantumphysics #quantumcomputing " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o07GLEfiZI4A9CVxIAAUIecPSls7OQADMC8jge?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=6G8cGdNAE%2FcGOXcjfZGII8Fd2nw%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o07GLEfiZI4A9CVxIAAUIecPSls7OQADMC8jge?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=6G8cGdNAE%2FcGOXcjfZGII8Fd2nw%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o07GLEfiZI4A9CVxIAAUIecPSls7OQADMC8jge?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=6G8cGdNAE%2FcGOXcjfZGII8Fd2nw%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

But here's why this is such a big deal: Remember how your parents taught you not to put all your eggs in one basket? Well, right now, the internet's eggs are mostly in some pretty risky baskets. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Gorillaz çš„ Dirty Harry (Instrumental) åˆ›ä½œçš„ How do you know if your information is on the dark web? Let's talk about how to actually CHECK for that. Here's the thing - you can't just Google your name on the dark web. But there ARE three major ways to find out if your info is out there. Number one: Go to haveibeenpwned.com. Type in your email, and it'll tell you if your data was leaked in any major breaches. Number two: Your bank probably already does dark web monitoring for free. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Are self driving cars really safer than when humans drive? Heres how they work technically so you can decide.  Self-driving cars work by using multiple sensors (cameras, radar, and LiDAR) to create a 360-degree view of their surroundings. These sensors act like the car's eyes and ears, constantly collecting data about nearby objects, road conditions, and traffic. A powerful computer system processes this information using artificial intelligence to understand what everything is (like pedestrians, other cars, or road signs) and predict how they might move. The AI then makes decisions about steering, braking, and acceleration - just like a human driver would, but using precise calculations. JavaScript and Python serve different main purposes - JavaScript was designed to make websites interactive and runs primarily in web browsers, while Python is a general-purpose language used for various tasks like data analysis, AI, and running programs on computers. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ How secure are password managers... really? Password managers store your login credentials in an encrypted vault. They work by: - Using a master password to generate a strong encryption key - Encrypting each password locally on your device - Storing the encrypted data locally or in the cloud - Decrypting passwords only when needed, using your master password To stay secure: -Create a strong master password (16+ characters, mix of characters) -Enable two-factor authentication with an authenticator app -Keep your devices and software updated -Set auto-lock timers and make regular backups -Watch for suspicious login attempts or sync errors #tech #technology #coding #strm #techexplained #techexpert " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/okIii9QgSeALcIjPwyjQZMeietGnCC8gPFMOFy?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=OUgy0Zj8JDi7EdVKcthylri%2FGVw%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/okIii9QgSeALcIjPwyjQZMeietGnCC8gPFMOFy?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=OUgy0Zj8JDi7EdVKcthylri%2FGVw%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/okIii9QgSeALcIjPwyjQZMeietGnCC8gPFMOFy?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=OUgy0Zj8JDi7EdVKcthylri%2FGVw%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Palali Music çš„ sonido original åˆ›ä½œçš„ RAM (Random Access Memory) is like a chef's workspace in a kitchen. It provides quick-access temporary storage for data that the computer's processor (the chef) needs to work with immediately. Just as a larger countertop allows a chef to handle more ingredients and tasks at once, more RAM enables a computer to run more programs simultaneously or handle larger files. When you turn off your computer, the RAM clears, similar to how a chef cleans their workspace after finishing. This temporary, fast-access nature of RAM is crucial for a computer's smooth operation, especially when multitasking. #tech #technology #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Save for your next tech interview ðŸ’¡ What happens when you type a URL into a browser?! First, the browser checks its cache for a stored version of the site. If not found, it contacts a Domain Name System (DNS) server to translate the domain name into an IP address. Using this IP address, the browser establishes a connection with the web server hosting the site through a protocol called TCP/IP. It then sends an HTTP request asking for the specific page. The server processes this request and sends back the necessary files (HTML, CSS, JavaScript, images, etc.) in an HTTP response. Finally, the browser renders these files, executing any scripts and applying styles to display the web page on your screen. #tech #technology #coding #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">
https://www.tiktok.com/@tiffintech/video/7424655194488638726
<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ What ia the difference between serverless computing and containers?! Serverless, managed by cloud providers, allows developers to focus on code, scales automatically, and charges only for compute time used. It's ideal for intermittent workloads but can face latency issues. Containers offer more control, run continuously, and suit complex applications better. A real-world example: A retail website might use serverless functions for product page views during a flash sale, scaling instantly to meet demand. Meanwhile, the persistent inventory management system could run in containers, maintaining constant uptime and state. This hybrid approach capitalizes on serverless for sporadic high traffic and containers for consistent, complex operations. #tech #technology #techexplained #stem " fetchpriority="auto" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ What exactly is DNS? This is something you might hear often in a tech interview or at a company you're working for. You can think of DNS like a phone book before the Internet. Just as you would use a phone book. Okay. Well, maybe we don't use phone books anymore. Our parents would use phone books to look up someone's name and phone number in the phone book. DNS helps your computer find the right website based on its domain name. When you type in. I love dogs. I mean, I know dogs are better than cats, let's face it. But regardless, when you type it in, computer doesn't actually know where to find. I love dogs dot com. It needs to translate this domain into an IP address, which is a unique numerical label that is assigned to each device connected to the internet. That's where DNS comes in. Your computer will send a request to the DNS server asking for the IP address of Isle of Dogs dot com, and the DNS server will respond with the correct IP address allowing your computer to connect to Isle of Dogs dot com website. And this process happens every single time you type in a website you want to visit. Save for your next tech interview.  #tech #stem #technology #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/fc0d2d3b324e46b5a299d9f94fa79d52_1728587275?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=XSkM2sNzDtAIHnLSSv7vjAUk5Fc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/fc0d2d3b324e46b5a299d9f94fa79d52_1728587275?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=XSkM2sNzDtAIHnLSSv7vjAUk5Fc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/fc0d2d3b324e46b5a299d9f94fa79d52_1728587275?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=XSkM2sNzDtAIHnLSSv7vjAUk5Fc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ The fact that humans invented all of this will forever blow my mind.  How do computers understand so many different programming languages?  Computers only truly understand machine code - instructions in 1s and 0s. Programming languages are tools that make it easier for humans to write instructions for computers. These languages work because: Translator programs convert human-friendly code into machine code. Languages have clear rules for how they should be translated. Computers are built to recognize common programming patterns. Some languages use helper systems to manage the translation process. It's like having a friend who seems to understand many languages, but is actually translating everything to their native tongue in their head. Similarly, computers appear to understand various programming languages, but are really just processing everything into their native binary language. #tech #technology #coding #stem #developer #computerscience #compsci " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/316f09d8f4054c2a9e5458ac99d2782f_1728503905?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=Q%2Fs2Bf2%2BxSNhQMe%2F09%2FzRVKbs8w%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/316f09d8f4054c2a9e5458ac99d2782f_1728503905?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=Q%2Fs2Bf2%2BxSNhQMe%2F09%2FzRVKbs8w%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/316f09d8f4054c2a9e5458ac99d2782f_1728503905?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=Q%2Fs2Bf2%2BxSNhQMe%2F09%2FzRVKbs8w%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ What is the difference between JavaScript vs Typescript?!  JavaScript and TypeScript are both programming languages used for web development, with TypeScript being a superset of JavaScript that adds optional static typing. While JavaScript is dynamic and flexible, allowing for quick development but potentially leading to runtime errors, TypeScript introduces static typing and compile-time checks. This helps catch errors earlier in the development process and can lead to more robust, maintainable code, especially in larger projects. TypeScript also offers better IDE support and enhanced object-oriented programming features. However, it comes with a steeper learning curve and requires a compilation step. JavaScript remains popular for its simplicity and is often preferred for smaller projects or rapid prototyping. #tech #technology #stem #developer " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-sg.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-alisg-p-0037/54950b56786a44c7a82baebf2916ea63_1727193326?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=eyJjz1QjeyOWgxb9xRM%2BGll8A5k%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-sg.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-alisg-p-0037/54950b56786a44c7a82baebf2916ea63_1727193326?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=eyJjz1QjeyOWgxb9xRM%2BGll8A5k%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-sg.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-alisg-p-0037/54950b56786a44c7a82baebf2916ea63_1727193326?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=eyJjz1QjeyOWgxb9xRM%2BGll8A5k%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Palali Music çš„ sonido original åˆ›ä½œçš„ What is quantum computing? In simple terms  Classical Computing: Uses bits - basic units of information that can be either 0 or 1 Processes information sequentially Best for everyday tasks like word processing, web browsing, etc. Quantum Computing: Uses qubits - can be 0, 1, or both simultaneously (superposition) Can process multiple possibilities at once Excels at specific complex problems like cryptography and molecular modeling The main advantage of quantum computing is its ability to perform certain calculations much faster than classical computers for particular types of problems. However, quantum computers are still in early stages of development and aren't yet practical for most everyday computing tasks. #tech #technology #coding #stem " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oMi3n1YiZsuudGZBESJUCyPj4kIBB3QtmdEMA?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=nWbyg4hxqfS%2BC9k1iL0kMfAGFA4%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oMi3n1YiZsuudGZBESJUCyPj4kIBB3QtmdEMA?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=nWbyg4hxqfS%2BC9k1iL0kMfAGFA4%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oMi3n1YiZsuudGZBESJUCyPj4kIBB3QtmdEMA?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=nWbyg4hxqfS%2BC9k1iL0kMfAGFA4%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Outkast çš„ Ms. Jackson (Instrumental) åˆ›ä½œçš„ What is the difference between GraphQL vs. REST? REST APIs are like traditional restaurant ordering, requiring multiple specific requests for different pieces of information, potentially over-delivering data, and needing menu updates for changes. In contrast, GraphQL is akin to a customizable ordering system, allowing a single request to fetch precisely the desired data, offering greater flexibility, and easily accommodating new options without overhauling the entire system. In essence, REST is like ordering from a traditional menu with set meals, while GraphQL is like having a fully customizable ordering system where you specify exactly what you want in one go.  #tech #technology #coding #stem " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/eab2772fb244406aa4f711fd7e9b83ca_1726854759?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=DmrZt4y3L%2BX%2FssURfPMJUO%2Fic%2B4%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/eab2772fb244406aa4f711fd7e9b83ca_1726854759?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=DmrZt4y3L%2BX%2FssURfPMJUO%2Fic%2B4%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/eab2772fb244406aa4f711fd7e9b83ca_1726854759?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=DmrZt4y3L%2BX%2FssURfPMJUO%2Fic%2B4%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Outkast çš„ Ms. Jackson (Instrumental) åˆ›ä½œçš„ Imagine a world without this invention?!ðŸ˜… This is Douglas Engelbart. And he solved a massive problem that we faced with computers.  Back in the 1960s, computers were massive, intimidating machines operated by punch cards and keyboards. Douglas envisioned a more seamless way to interact with them.  Therefore, he and his team at Stanford began experimenting with various pointing devices, including a knee-operated pointer and a stylus. BUT these early attempts were impractical for everyday use. Engelbart persisted, eventually crafting a wooden shell housing two metal wheels. BUT at the time, most people interacted with computers through complex command-line interfaces or punch card systems. The mouse remained largely unknown outside of research circles for years. BUT as personal computers began to emerge in the late 1970s, the need for user-friendly interfaces became apparent. THEREFORE, companies like Apple began to take notice of Engelbart's invention. BUT it wasn't until 1984, with the release of the Apple Macintosh, that the mouse finally found its way into the hands of everyday users. Engelbart's perseverance and vision ultimately transformed how we interact with computers, even if it took nearly two decades for his invention to achieve widespread recognition and use. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Palali Music çš„ sonido original åˆ›ä½œçš„ What is the difference between Docker and Virtual Machines?  Virtual machines and Docker are both technologies used to run applications in isolated environments, but they work differently. A virtual machine (VM) is like a complete computer running inside your actual computer. It has its own operating system and uses a portion of your computer's resources to run as if it were a separate machine. Docker, on the other hand, uses containers. These containers share the host computer's operating system kernel but are isolated from each other. They're lighter and faster to start up than VMs because they don't need a full OS for each application. Think of VMs as separate apartments in a building, each with its own utilities, while Docker containers are more like efficient, self-contained rooms that share the building's main systems. #tech #technology #techexplained #stem #developer " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ecdc11149f4a4ecb89a6556b4674859f_1726505694?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=IXb03DcV3sEg0X%2B5Sxt2FX6%2B4C8%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ecdc11149f4a4ecb89a6556b4674859f_1726505694?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=IXb03DcV3sEg0X%2B5Sxt2FX6%2B4C8%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ecdc11149f4a4ecb89a6556b4674859f_1726505694?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=IXb03DcV3sEg0X%2B5Sxt2FX6%2B4C8%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Palali Music çš„ sonido original åˆ›ä½œçš„ What is the difference between SQL and NoSQL?  Think of SQL and NoSQL databases like different types of storage systems. SQL is like a traditional library with strict organization - books are in specific places and there's a detailed catalog. It's great for finding exact information but less flexible. NoSQL is more like a modern, adaptable storage system - think adjustable shelves or bins. It's easier to add new types of items quickly, but might be less organized. SQL works well for applications needing precise data handling, like banking. NoSQL is better for apps dealing with varied, rapidly changing data, like social media. Essentially, SQL is a structured filing system, while NoSQL offers more flexible storage options. #tech #techexplained #developer #coding " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/f2401124223747a5b5b8ec548c55cf7b_1726257091?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=e8tS7w6Ly6I%2BY%2FDfCXhARU3QSOk%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/f2401124223747a5b5b8ec548c55cf7b_1726257091?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=e8tS7w6Ly6I%2BY%2FDfCXhARU3QSOk%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/f2401124223747a5b5b8ec548c55cf7b_1726257091?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=e8tS7w6Ly6I%2BY%2FDfCXhARU3QSOk%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Palali Music çš„ sonido original åˆ›ä½œçš„ How does Starlink work?  Starlink is a satellite internet constellation operated by SpaceX. It consists of thousands of small satellites in low Earth orbit (LEO), typically at altitudes of 540-570 km. These satellites communicate with ground-based transceivers using phased array antennas and high-frequency Ku and Ka band radio waves. The satellites form a mesh network in space, using laser inter-satellite links to route data between them. This allows for global coverage and reduces latency compared to traditional geostationary satellite internet. Ground stations, called gateways, connect the satellite network to the broader internet infrastructure. User terminals, known as &quot;Starlink dishes,&quot; use electronically steered beams to track and communicate with multiple satellites as they pass overhead, ensuring continuous connectivity. #tech #technology #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o0EIdFNcfEA8CfDhIf52ASAgEd9Q4ur4rDTAjP?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=IBxsX8dhZ%2BK8tT0h5o8Ap1keF7E%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o0EIdFNcfEA8CfDhIf52ASAgEd9Q4ur4rDTAjP?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=IBxsX8dhZ%2BK8tT0h5o8Ap1keF7E%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o0EIdFNcfEA8CfDhIf52ASAgEd9Q4ur4rDTAjP?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=IBxsX8dhZ%2BK8tT0h5o8Ap1keF7E%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Palali Music çš„ sonido original åˆ›ä½œçš„ What is Git?  Git is a distributed version control system that helps developers track and manage changes in their code. A typical Git workflow involves cloning a repository, creating a new branch for a feature or fix, making changes locally, staging these changes with 'git add', committing them with 'git commit', and then pushing the changes to a remote repository with 'git push'. Developers often create a pull request for code review, after which the changes are merged into the main branch. This process allows for collaborative development, easy tracking of project history, and the ability to work on multiple features simultaneously without affecting the main codebase until changes are ready and reviewed. #tech #technology #coding #stem #techtok " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/69cd2255def1456a9427fa5cfc12d432_1725296221?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=QWIgiiqTGouhsL3ry7jdexuxbAM%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/69cd2255def1456a9427fa5cfc12d432_1725296221?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=QWIgiiqTGouhsL3ry7jdexuxbAM%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/69cd2255def1456a9427fa5cfc12d432_1725296221?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=QWIgiiqTGouhsL3ry7jdexuxbAM%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">
