<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ The King Khan &amp; BBQ Show çš„ Love You So åˆ›ä½œçš„ A simple way to explain and understand what is DNS for a tech interview or if you hear it in a meeting.  Imagine you're trying to find the address of a house. You might use a map to locate the street, but you still need to know the house number to find the right place. Similarly, when you want to visit a website, you need to know its address or URL (Uniform Resource Locator). But instead of memorizing a bunch of numbers, we use domain names like google.  Now, how does your computer know where to find the website when you type in the domain name? That's where DNS (Domain Name System) comes in. DNS is like a phone book for the internet. When you type in a domain name, your computer sends a request to a DNS server, which looks up the IP (Internet Protocol) address associated with that domain name. An IP address is a unique numerical identifier that identifies the computer or server hosting the website. Once the DNS server finds the IP address, it sends it back to your computer, which can then connect to the web server hosting the website using that IP address. Think of it like looking up a phone number in a phone book and dialing it to connect to the person you want to talk to. DNS is important because it makes it easy for us to access websites and other internet resources without having to remember long strings of numbers. It also allows us to quickly switch between different servers or services that might be hosted on different IP addresses, while still using the same easy-to-remember domain name." fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/owHISw9P7CeESAejTCuIcb9BlfIgg5bvnyLnDO?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=slygp391Nrml9xenBwjgIrZaE4E%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/owHISw9P7CeESAejTCuIcb9BlfIgg5bvnyLnDO?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=slygp391Nrml9xenBwjgIrZaE4E%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/owHISw9P7CeESAejTCuIcb9BlfIgg5bvnyLnDO?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=slygp391Nrml9xenBwjgIrZaE4E%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ dtuhstuhd34 çš„ Ac r7sheed åˆ›ä½œçš„ Gone are the days where you can solely rely on technical skills without building soft skills. You absolutely need both (if you are a technical person). Here is some insight into the top soft skills to focus on.  1. Communication: Strong communication skills are essential for tech professionals as they need to be able to effectively express complex concepts and ideas in a way that is understandable to both technical and non-technical people. 2. Leadership: Tech professionals must have the ability to lead projects, develop innovative solutions, and motivate teams of individuals with different skill sets. 3. Problem Solving: In the tech industry, problem solving goes beyond coding; it involves being able to think creatively in order to overcome challenges while staying on track with deadlines and expectations from clients or other stakeholders.  4. Collaboration: Working together requires good interpersonal skills in order for everyone involved to function efficiently as a team toward achieving common goals. It also entails knowing how each member can best contribute their individual talents or strengths toward success.  5. Adaptability &amp; Flexibility: Technology changes rapidly so tech professionals must stay up-to-date with current trends and developments within their field which often necessitates quick adaptation of new information or processes into existing systems or products.. #learnontiktok #techcareer #stem #futuretech #career #techtok #softwareengineering " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oEPB9CnV8eR36oXewRTMABVENndQgJEbQj8d6D?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=cBWtnimjp2kzlKo37K9KrqkjLm8%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oEPB9CnV8eR36oXewRTMABVENndQgJEbQj8d6D?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=cBWtnimjp2kzlKo37K9KrqkjLm8%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oEPB9CnV8eR36oXewRTMABVENndQgJEbQj8d6D?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=cBWtnimjp2kzlKo37K9KrqkjLm8%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Miley Cyrus çš„ Flowers åˆ›ä½œçš„ There are many technical aspects as to what is takes to keep a massive app running (somewhat) smoothly!  Load balancing: distributing traffic evenly across multiple servers to prevent any one from becoming overwhelmed. Caching: storing frequently requested data temporarily in a cache to reduce server load and speed up responses. Database sharding: dividing large databases into smaller, more manageable parts to improve query performance and reduce load on the database. Content delivery networks (CDN): caching and serving static content such as images and videos closer to users to reduce network latency. Microservices architecture: breaking the application down into smaller, self-contained services to improve scalability and reliability. These and other techniques allow Instagram to handle high traffic while maintaining performance and availability. #learnontiktok #techexplained #tech #techtok " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ogbjYDhABCBDZ4QAKgnRJjQp2IfOKNRHDe6EPD?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=2C9k1ylPM%2B0STwnb%2FlxKqAnlaFQ%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ogbjYDhABCBDZ4QAKgnRJjQp2IfOKNRHDe6EPD?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=2C9k1ylPM%2B0STwnb%2FlxKqAnlaFQ%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ogbjYDhABCBDZ4QAKgnRJjQp2IfOKNRHDe6EPD?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=2C9k1ylPM%2B0STwnb%2FlxKqAnlaFQ%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Heinz Kiessling çš„ Blue Blood åˆ›ä½œçš„ How are passwords stored in databases? In order to store passwords in a database in a secure way, it is common to use a process called hashing. Hashing is a one-way function that takes an input (in this case, a password) and generates a fixed-size string of characters, known as a hash. The same input will always produce the same hash, but it is not possible to determine the original input from the hash. One important property of hashing is that it is computationally infeasible to generate the same hash for two different inputs. This means that if two different passwords are hashed, it is very unlikely that they will produce the same hash. In order to store a password in a database, the password is first hashed and the resulting hash is stored instead of the original password. When a user attempts to log in, the password they enter is hashed and the resulting hash is checked against the hash stored in the database. If the hashes match, the user is authenticated. However, there are certain types of attacks that can be used to try and determine the original password from a hash, such as a rainbow table attack. To make it more difficult for these types of attacks to be successful, it is common to use a technique called salting. Salting involves adding a random string of characters, known as a salt, to the password before hashing it. This means that even if two users have the same password, the hashes stored in the database will be different because the salt is different. This makes it much more difficult for an attacker to use a pre-computed hash table to try and determine the original passwords. In summary, to store and retrieve passwords in a database, the following process is used: âž¡ï¸ the password is combined with a random salt. âž¡ï¸ the combined password and salt are hashed. âž¡ï¸ the resulting hash and the salt are stored in the database. âž¡ï¸ when a user attempts to log in, their password is combined with the salt stored in the database and the resulting combined string is hashed. âž¡ï¸ the resulting hash is compared to the hash stored in the database. If the hashes match, the user is authenticated. #stem #learnontiktok #learntocode #tech #futureethis #edutok #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYCag3NzkEJBIoxCYVqDi1y6vAAAkhj9fBGIIo~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/3228c547ee564445a015fe4e6b42d2b5.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=MbFH8UZep0s2gAvCVeDyfYWwPdg%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYCag3NzkEJBIoxCYVqDi1y6vAAAkhj9fBGIIo~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/3228c547ee564445a015fe4e6b42d2b5.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=MbFH8UZep0s2gAvCVeDyfYWwPdg%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYCag3NzkEJBIoxCYVqDi1y6vAAAkhj9fBGIIo~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/3228c547ee564445a015fe4e6b42d2b5.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=MbFH8UZep0s2gAvCVeDyfYWwPdg%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Heinz Kiessling çš„ Blue Blood åˆ›ä½œçš„ How to explain what is DNS? ðŸ‘‡  To understand how DNS works, think of it like a phonebook or directory for the internet. When a user types in a domain name, their computer sends out a query through the DNS system looking up the associated IP address with that domain name. The DNS server then responds back with the corresponding IP address of where the website is located on the web server.  For example, when you type â€œwww.example.comâ€ into your browser bar, your computer will first send out a request to its local DNS cache for any cached information about that domain name; if none exists, it will then send out another query to its assigned DNS server asking for assistance in finding where this website is located on the web server so that content associated with it can be displayed to you on your screen. Once a response has been received from the DNS server, your computer will have access to all of the records associated with that particular website and it will be able to direct you to its content on your web browser window. " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/39e324b0cee0474b8a93229639a2a4ed_1672160970~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/afb516431e4c4b17b469c0c788ac8977.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=fA95wn9SkuU2iAQxZfUtyBQq2RE%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/39e324b0cee0474b8a93229639a2a4ed_1672160970~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/afb516431e4c4b17b469c0c788ac8977.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=fA95wn9SkuU2iAQxZfUtyBQq2RE%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/39e324b0cee0474b8a93229639a2a4ed_1672160970~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/afb516431e4c4b17b469c0c788ac8977.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=fA95wn9SkuU2iAQxZfUtyBQq2RE%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Heinz Kiessling çš„ Blue Blood åˆ›ä½œçš„ Why Spotify Shuffle is Not Truly Random? Have you ever noticed that Spotify shuffle mode isn't really random? Yeah me too.  After using Spotify for many years myself and many others started realizing that some songs appear more than others.  But why does this happen? Shouldn't it be completely random? The short answer is no.  According to a former software Spotify engineer between 2012 and 2017 algorithm used to work perfectly random years ago. Thanks to a Fisher Yates algorithm. What is the Fisher Yates algorithm you ask? Take a look at this image. Which one seems more random? The first one right?  When thinking about a random algorithm the human brain tends to lean more towards the first one that it would make more random results than the second one.  However in the fisher yates algorithm they both equally could appear.  When the second lines appear they create a confusion among Spotify users who felt like finding the same songs in a row wasn't really random at all. So in 2014 Spotify actually changed its algorithm from being completely random to a new algorithm to appeal to the human brain.  For example if you had a play with with songs from Taylor Swift, Beyonce and say Drake, you sadly would never get 5 Beyonce songs in a row.  Although in a true random scenario the result would be entirely possible. But for the human brain it makes it think that the random algorithm is actually broken.  Our brains cannot process the concept of random very well and it's in our nature to look for patterns and ways to solve it.  #stem #techexplained #tech #technology #learntocode #futuretech #computerscience " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/okkzqzy0hOJAIJfoxj2AnoEtV9EIAoC1oEgpO2~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/2bc1ef1d00cd43b7a804488a8a14d94f.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=8VQsFow9dcDmggvOnsqGzCFI0ig%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/okkzqzy0hOJAIJfoxj2AnoEtV9EIAoC1oEgpO2~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/2bc1ef1d00cd43b7a804488a8a14d94f.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=8VQsFow9dcDmggvOnsqGzCFI0ig%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/okkzqzy0hOJAIJfoxj2AnoEtV9EIAoC1oEgpO2~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/2bc1ef1d00cd43b7a804488a8a14d94f.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=8VQsFow9dcDmggvOnsqGzCFI0ig%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

Save this for your next tech interview ðŸ‘‡ðŸ’¡ I have a tech interview coming up and they're going to ask me about a firewall. How do I easily explain it? <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Heinz Kiessling çš„ Blue Blood åˆ›ä½œçš„ How to explain HTTP request in a tech interview? What are HTTP requests?   HTTP/1 to HTTP/2 to HTTP/3. What do these numbers mean and why should you care? In the world of technology, it is important to stay ahead of the curve.  HTTP/1 was the first http protocol released in the 90s. It was designed to send and receive webpages from a server. This protocol worked by establishing separate data connections for each of the http requests sent by the client or browser. Because of this, http/1 was slow and prone to latency issues.  HTTP 1.1 came soon after  It introduced a keep alive mechanism   In 2015, http/2 was released as an upgrade to http/1, designed to improve performance and reduce latency. This solved the problem of http/1's slow speed and made webpages load faster. It also introduced header compression, allowing http headers to be compressed and reducing the amount of data sent over the connection.  The latest http protocol, http/3, was released in 2018. http/3 can transmit data up to three times faster than http/2, as well as being more secure due to its encryption. http/3 also supports multiplexing and header compression, building upon the features of http/2.  #stem #tech #techexplained #compsci #coding #techeducation #womeninstem " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/7d8ad001a3a84beb922f68f96f99e294_1669232293?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=jGjz4KHb7Anj0BcE6Y9%2FNZody6o%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/7d8ad001a3a84beb922f68f96f99e294_1669232293?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=jGjz4KHb7Anj0BcE6Y9%2FNZody6o%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/7d8ad001a3a84beb922f68f96f99e294_1669232293?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=jGjz4KHb7Anj0BcE6Y9%2FNZody6o%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Echosmith çš„ Cool Kids (our sped up version) åˆ›ä½œçš„ What are RESTful APIs and some benefits? Hereâ€™s how to explain it in under 30 seconds!   REST is a set of architectural constraints, not a protocol or a standard. API developers can implement REST in a variety of ways.  When a client request is made via a RESTful API, it transfers a representation of the state of the resource to the requester or endpoint.  (resource: RedHat) #tech #technology #techeducation #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ok2CgQNzkEIoIxxCDiREVtW0uApAshSKfBTSIo?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=33lP0hIxDO6OcEe3ZosMJmpl%2FUw%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ok2CgQNzkEIoIxxCDiREVtW0uApAshSKfBTSIo?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=33lP0hIxDO6OcEe3ZosMJmpl%2FUw%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ok2CgQNzkEIoIxxCDiREVtW0uApAshSKfBTSIo?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=33lP0hIxDO6OcEe3ZosMJmpl%2FUw%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Echosmith çš„ Cool Kids (our sped up version) åˆ›ä½œçš„ What is the difference between SQL and NoSQL and which one to learn first? ðŸ’¡  SQL databases are primarily called as Relational Databases (RDBMS); whereas NoSQL database are primarily called as non-relational. <img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Funk Tribu çš„ Phonky Tribu åˆ›ä½œçš„ When I first entered the tech world there were ALOT of phrases I was confused about ðŸ¤£ here are some of them!   Yoda Conditions: When a programmer writes the conditions for a piece of code in the opposite order for which you would expect to normally read them. (Instead of saying if(variable == constant), the code says if(constant == variable).)  Heisenbug: A play on &quot;Heisenberg,&quot; a principle in quantum mechanics, a Heisenbug is a bug that disappears or alters its characteristics when an attempt is made to study it.  Jenga code: The whole program collapses once you alter a block of code.  Common law feature: A bug that has existed for so long that it is considered a feature.  #stem #tech #techtoktips " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/1033532a43ff4638aaf12c3a9be419b8?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=KndsQbn%2FyHpfTd78N%2BV4GYPepaM%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/1033532a43ff4638aaf12c3a9be419b8?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=KndsQbn%2FyHpfTd78N%2BV4GYPepaM%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/1033532a43ff4638aaf12c3a9be419b8?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=KndsQbn%2FyHpfTd78N%2BV4GYPepaM%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech ä½¿ç”¨ Tiff in Tech çš„ original sound åˆ›ä½œçš„ Ever wonder why all of the voice assistants are female? From Siri, to Alexa, Bank of America's Erica and more, we listen to female voices answer our requests daily. Why did these big tech companies choose female voices? And is there an impact on us that this will have? This is a high level summary of why many voice assistants are female.
